subsection.p:
To arrive at Maxwell's discovery we seek a solution of his equations in region of space that has no currents (\vec J = 0) or charges (\rho = 0), so-called empty space or vacuum. 

	 \amp \vec{\nabla}\cdot \vec E = 0 
	 \amp \vec{\nabla}\cdot \vec B = 0 
	 \amp \vec{\nabla}\times \vec E = -\frac{\partial \vec B}{\partial t} 
	 \amp \vec{\nabla}\times \vec B =\mu_0\epsilon_0 \frac{\partial \vec E}{\partial t}

If the material is perfectly reflecting such as the metal surface and if the incidence is along the normal to the surface, then the pressure exerted will be twice as much since the momentum direction will reverse upon reflection and conservation of momentum will imply

	P_{\text{rad}} = 2u. \ \ \text{(Perfect reflector)}

Do not confuse P_{\text{rad}}  with the power.  Let's see if the units are right.

	[u] = \frac{\text{J}}{\text{m}^3} = \frac{\text{N.m}}{\text{m}^3} = \frac{\text{N}}{\text{m}^2} = \text{unit of pressure!}

Equations   and   give instantaneous pressure, but since  energy density of EM wave oscillates rapidly, we are usually interested in the time-averaged quantity, as was the case with our interest in intensity. The time average of radiation pressure can be expressed in terms of intensity also.

	P_{\text{ave}}^{\text{rad}} = 
		\begin{cases}
		I/c \amp \quad \text{Perfect absorber}\\
		2I/c \amp \quad \text{Perfect reflector}
		\end{cases}
